title: JavaTreeSet - Q0001
text: Which package contains the TreeSet class?
explanation: The TreeSet class is part of the java.util package.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0002
text: Which interface does TreeSet implement?
explanation: TreeSet implements the NavigableSet interface.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0003
text: Which data structure does TreeSet use internally?
explanation: TreeSet uses a TreeMap internally to store its elements.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0004
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and duplicates?

options.text: TreeSet does not allow duplicate elements

explanation: TreeSet does not allow duplicate elements.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0005
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and null elements?

options.text: TreeSet does not allow null elements
TreeSet throws NullPointerException only for duplicates

explanation: TreeSet does not allow null elements because it uses natural ordering or a comparator.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0006
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and ordering?

options.text: TreeSet maintains elements in sorted order

explanation: TreeSet maintains elements in sorted order according to their natural ordering or a comparator.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0007
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and synchronization?
explanation: TreeSet is not synchronized and is not thread-safe by default.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0008
text: Which of the following methods can be used to synchronize a TreeSet?
explanation: The Collections.synchronizedSortedSet() method returns a synchronized version of the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0009
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and iteration order?
explanation: TreeSet iterates elements in sorted order.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0010
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and performance?

options.text: TreeSet provides O(log n) time for add, remove, and contains
TreeSet provides O(1) time for add, remove, and contains
TreeSet provides O(n) time for add, remove, and contains
TreeSet provides O(n^2) time for add, remove, and contains

explanation: TreeSet provides O(log n) time complexity for add, remove, and contains operations.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0011
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and duplicates detection?

options.text: Duplicates are detected using compareTo() or Comparator

explanation: TreeSet uses compareTo() or Comparator to detect duplicates.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0012
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and null handling?

options.text: TreeSet throws NullPointerException for null elements

explanation: TreeSet throws NullPointerException when null is added because it cannot compare null values.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0013
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and internal ordering?

options.text: TreeSet uses natural ordering or a custom comparator
TreeSet uses hash codes for ordering

explanation: TreeSet uses natural ordering or a custom comparator for sorting elements.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0014
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and comparator?

options.text: TreeSet can use a custom comparator for sorting

explanation: TreeSet can use a custom comparator for sorting elements.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0015
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and first()?
explanation: The first() method returns the lowest element in the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0016
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and last()?
explanation: The last() method returns the highest element in the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0017
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and headSet()?

options.text: headSet() returns elements less than a given element
headSet() returns elements greater than a given element

explanation: The headSet() method returns elements less than the specified element.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0018
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and tailSet()?

options.text: tailSet() returns elements greater than or equal to a given element
tailSet() returns elements less than a given element

explanation: The tailSet() method returns elements greater than or equal to the specified element.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0019
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and subSet()?

options.text: subSet() returns elements between two specified elements

explanation: The subSet() method returns elements between two specified elements.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0020
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and descendingSet()?

options.text: descendingSet() returns a reverse order view of the set
descendingSet() returns a sorted order view

explanation: The descendingSet() method returns a reverse order view of the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0021
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and iterator()?

options.text: iterator() returns elements in ascending order
iterator() returns elements in random order
iterator() returns elements in insertion order
iterator() returns elements in reverse order

explanation: The iterator() method of TreeSet returns elements in ascending order.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0022
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and descendingIterator()?

options.text: descendingIterator() returns elements in reverse order
descendingIterator() returns elements in ascending order

explanation: The descendingIterator() method returns an iterator that traverses the set in reverse order.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0023
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and comparator()?

options.text: comparator() returns the comparator used for ordering

explanation: The comparator() method returns the comparator used for ordering, or null if natural ordering is used.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0024
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and pollFirst()?

options.text: pollFirst() retrieves and removes the lowest element
pollFirst() retrieves and removes the highest element
pollFirst() retrieves but does not remove the lowest element

explanation: The pollFirst() method retrieves and removes the lowest element of the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0025
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and pollLast()?

options.text: pollLast() retrieves and removes the highest element
pollLast() retrieves and removes the lowest element
pollLast() retrieves but does not remove the highest element

explanation: The pollLast() method retrieves and removes the highest element of the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0026
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and ceiling()?

options.text: ceiling() returns the least element greater than or equal to the given element
ceiling() returns the greatest element less than or equal to the given element

explanation: The ceiling() method returns the least element greater than or equal to the given element.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0027
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and floor()?

options.text: floor() returns the greatest element less than or equal to the given element
floor() returns the least element greater than or equal to the given element

explanation: The floor() method returns the greatest element less than or equal to the given element.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0028
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and higher()?

options.text: higher() returns the least element strictly greater than the given element
higher() returns the greatest element less than the given element

explanation: The higher() method returns the least element strictly greater than the given element.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0029
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and lower()?

options.text: lower() returns the greatest element strictly less than the given element
lower() returns the least element greater than the given element

explanation: The lower() method returns the greatest element strictly less than the given element.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0030
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and clone()?

options.text: clone() creates a shallow copy of the set
clone() creates a deep copy of the set

explanation: The clone() method creates a shallow copy of the TreeSet.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0031
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and serialization?

options.text: TreeSet cannot be written to a stream

explanation: TreeSet implements Serializable, allowing it to be serialized.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0032
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and thread safety?
explanation: TreeSet is not thread-safe; external synchronization is required.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0033
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and iteration performance?
explanation: Iterating through a TreeSet requires visiting each element, making it O(n).

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0034
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and equals()?
explanation: The equals() method compares elements for equality.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0035
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and hashCode()?
explanation: The hashCode() of a TreeSet depends on the hash codes of its elements.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0036
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and immutability?
explanation: TreeSet is mutable; elements can be added or removed.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0037
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and removeIf()?

options.text: removeIf() removes elements matching a condition

explanation: The removeIf() method removes elements that satisfy a given predicate condition.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0038
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and forEach()?

options.text: forEach() performs an action for each element

explanation: The forEach() method performs the specified action for each element in the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0039
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and stream()?

options.text: stream() returns a sequential stream of elements

explanation: The stream() method returns a sequential stream of elements from the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0040
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and parallelStream()?

options.text: parallelStream() returns a parallel stream of elements

explanation: The parallelStream() method returns a parallel stream of elements from the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0041
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and comparator usage?
explanation: Comparator defines custom sorting logic for TreeSet elements.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0042
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and natural ordering?

options.text: Natural ordering is based on Comparable interface
Natural ordering is based on hashCode()
Natural ordering is based on equals()

explanation: Natural ordering in TreeSet is based on the Comparable interface implementation.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0043
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and fail-fast behavior?
explanation: TreeSet iterators are fail-fast and throw ConcurrentModificationException if modified during iteration.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0044
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and remove()?
explanation: The remove() method deletes the specified element from the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0045
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and clear()?
explanation: The clear() method removes all elements from the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0046
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and size()?

options.text: size() returns the number of elements

explanation: The size() method returns the number of elements in the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0047
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and isEmpty()?

options.text: isEmpty() checks if the set has no elements

explanation: The isEmpty() method checks if the set contains no elements.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0048
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and contains()?

options.text: contains() checks if an element exists in the set

explanation: The contains() method checks if an element exists in the set.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0049
text: Which of the following is true about TreeSet and add()?

options.text: add() adds an element if not already present

explanation: The add() method adds an element only if it is not already present.

title: JavaTreeSet - Q0050
text: Which of the following best describes TreeSet?

options.text: A sorted set implementation based on a balanced tree

explanation: TreeSet is a sorted set implementation based on a balanced tree (Red-Black tree).
